'''Janet Lembke''' (2 March 1933 – 3 September 2013), ''née'' Janet Nutt, was an American author, essayist, naturalist, translator and scholar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.southernnature.org/event-news-profile.php?News_ID=44 |title=Author Janet Lembke Dies at Age 80 |publisher=Southernnature.org |date=2013-09-05 |accessdate=2014-01-09}}</ref> She was born in Cleveland, Ohio during the [[Great Depression]], graduated in 1953 from [[Middlebury College]], [[Vermont]], with a degree in [[Classics]],<ref name="lembke_papers" /> and her knowledge of the classical Greek and Latin worldview, from [[Homer]] to [[Virgil]], informed her life and work. A Certified [https://web.archive.org/web/20140109045424/http://www.hort.vt.edu/mastergardener/ Virginia Master Gardener],<ref name="poets_writers">[http://www.pw.org/content/janet_lembke_2 Janet Lembke entry in ''Poets & Writers'' directory]</ref> she lived in Virginia and North Carolina, drawing inspiration from both locales. She was recognized for her creative view of natural cycles, agriculture and of animals, both domestic and wild, with whom we share the natural environment. Referred to as an "acclaimed Southern naturalist,"<ref name="barnes_touching">[http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/touching-earth-janet-lembke/1004542082?ean=9781580800884 Barnes & Noble review of ''Touching Earth'' by Janet Lembke]</ref> she was equally (as [[The Chicago Tribune]] described her) a "classicist, a noted Oxford University Press translator of the works of Sophocles, Euripides and Aeschylus".<ref name="chicago_tribune">{{cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1995-01-26/features/9501260188_1_skinny-dipping-essay-water-flows|title=Janet Lembke's Essays Get The Skinny On Essentials|last=Leardi|first=Jeanette|date=26 January 1995|work=[[The Chicago Tribune]]|accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> She received a grant from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]] to translate [[Virgil]]'s [[Georgics]],<ref name="poets_writers" /> having already translated [[Euripides]]' ''Electra'' and ''Hecuba'', and [[Aeschylus]]'s ''Persians'' and ''Suppliants''.

Janet Lembke's first book was ''Bronze and Iron: Old Latin Poetry from Its Beginnings to 100 B.C.'' (1973), but beyond  translations and essays about classics, there were more than a dozen books on nature, works for which the author acquired a base of admirers. Her articles were printed in [[The New York Times]], ''[http://www.sierraclub.org/sierra/ Sierra Magazine]'' ([[The Sierra Club]]), [[Oxford American]], [[Audubon (magazine)|Audubon]], [[Raleigh News and Observer]], [[Southern Review]] and other publications. The writing style was eclectic and personal, meditative and detailed, and though she was at least once accused of "taking poetic license too far"<ref name="bryn_mawr">[http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2005/2005-08-06.html Criticism of Lembke's translation of ''The Georgics'']. ''Bryn Mawr Classical Review'' 2005</ref> in her translation of ''Georgics'', readers were often charmed and seduced by her way of weaving scientific fact, history and culture, with personal anecdote, mythological allusion and poetic feeling. "The author's ability to pull together disparate elements in her writing is impressive, and her passionate connection with the natural world is displayed in line after line," wrote [[The New York Times]].<ref name="skinnydipping_nyt">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/12/18/books/in-short-nonfiction-040029.html|title=SKINNY DIPPING And Other Immersions in Water, Myth, and Being Human. By Janet Lembke.|last=Hanson|first=Elizabeth|date=18 December 1994|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=6 January 2014}}</ref> Novelist [[Annie Proulx]] expressed a similar perception, observing that "Lembke's writing tacks between three points: the stuff of her late-twentieth-century life; the tangle of creature and plant in every dimension of tide and river flow; and the haunting, connecting wires of mythos that still knot us  to the ancient beginnings."<ref name="Lembke2003">Annie Proulx on Lembke: {{cite book|author=Janet Lembke|title=The Quality of Life: Living Well, Dying Well|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mDNtM_f1tdEC&pg=PA214|year=2003|publisher=[[Lyons Press]]|isbn=978-1-59228-128-2|pages=214–}}</ref>

Among Janet Lembke's noted titles were ''Because the Cat Purrs: How We Relate to Other Species and Why It Matters'' (2008); ''Skinny Dipping: And Other Immersions in Water, Myth, and Being Human'' (2004); ''Dangerous Birds'' (1996); ''River Time'' (1997); ''Despicable Species: On Cowbirds, Kudzu, Hornworms, and Other Scourges'' (1999); and ''The Quality of Life: Living Well, Dying Well'' (2004)-- a sober and unflinching account of the death of the author's mother. At the time of her own death at age 80 in [[Staunton, Virginia|Staunton]], [[Virginia (state)|Virginia]], Janet Lembke was working on a memoir, ''I Married an Arsonist''. She had married twice, and had four children and six grandchildren.<ref name="janet_obit">{{cite news|url=http://www.newsleader.com/article/20130905/OBITUARIES/309050008 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20140110102633/http://www.newsleader.com/article/20130905/OBITUARIES/309050008 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=10 January 2014 |title=Obituary: Janet N. Lembke |date=5 September 2013 |work=Staunton News Leader |accessdate=8 January 2014 }}</ref>

There is a repository of archived materials ("The Janet Lembke Papers, 1966 - 2008"), including notes and correspondence by the author, at the Jackson Library of the [[University of North Carolina]] in Greensboro, NC.<ref name="lembke_papers">[http://library.uncg.edu/info/depts/scua/collections/manuscripts/ead/mss263.xml The Janet Lembke Papers, 1966 - 2008] at University of North Carolina</ref>

